 To hide the body of an HTML document, you can set its `display` style property to `none` using JavaScript. Here's a simple example:

```javascript
document.body.style.display = 'none';
```

To show it again, simply set the `display` property back to its original value, typically 'block':

```javascript
document.body.style.display = 'block';
```

Here's how you can create a function in JavaScript to toggle the visibility of the body:

```javascript
function toggleBodyVisibility() {
  const body = document.body;
  const currentDisplay = getComputedStyle(body).display;

  if (currentDisplay === 'none') {
    body.style.display = 'block';
  } else {
    body.style.display = 'none';
  }
}

// To use the function
toggleBodyVisibility();
```

This function checks the current display style of the body, and if it's set to `none`, it changes it to 'block' to show it again. If it's set to anything else, it sets it to `none` to hide it.

Alternatively, if you want to use CSS for hiding and showing the body based on some conditions (like a button click), you can define CSS classes for hiding and showing:

```css
.hide {
  display: none;
}

.show {
  display: block;
}
```

Then use JavaScript to add or remove the appropriate class:

```javascript
document.body.classList.add('hide'); // To hide the body
document.body.classList.remove('hide');
document.body.classList.add('show'); // To show the body
document.body.classList.remove('show');
```

Remember to include these classes in your HTML elements or to define them in your CSS file.

